<exercises xml:id="exercises-1-1">
  <title>Exercises for Section 1.1</title>

  <introduction>
  Below are the exercises to complete for this section. You can check many of the answers in 
  the "backmatter" of these notes. The necessary calculus pre-reqs for these exercises are listed at the bottom of this page.

  </introduction>

  <exercise xml:id="ex-1-1-1">
    <statement>
      <p>
        Write a differential equation where the solution <m>y(x)</m> has the property that the slope of its graph at any point <m>(x, y)</m> equals the sum of <m>x</m> and <m>y</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
    <answer>
      <p><me>\frac{dy}{dx} = x + y</me></p>
    </answer>
  </exercise>

  <exercise xml:id="ex-1-1-2">
    <statement>
      <p>
        Write a differential equation where the solution <m>y(x)</m> has the property that the tangent line to its graph at any point <m>(x, y)</m> passes through the point <m>(-y,\, x)</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
    <hint>
      <p>
        You will need to use the fact that the slope of any line is <m>\frac{y_1-y_0}{x_1-x_0}</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
        Compute the slope of the tangent line: one of the points it passes through is <m>(-y,\, x)</m>, what other point does the
        tangent line always pass through?
        Refer to the setting up ODEs example in the notes.
      </p>
    </hint>
    <answer>
      <p><me>\frac{dy}{dx} = \frac{x - y}{x + y}</me></p>
    </answer>
  </exercise>

 <exercise xml:id="ex-1-1-3">
  <statement>
    <p>
      The temperature <m>T</m> of a cup of coffee changes at a rate proportional to 
      the difference between the ambient air temperature and the coffee's current temperature. 
      Suppose the ambient air temperature is <m>65^\circ</m>F. Write a differential equation modeling <m>T(t)</m>.
    </p>
  </statement>
  <answer>
    <p>
      <me>\frac{dT}{dt} = k(T - 65)</me>
      Or equivalently: 
      <me>\frac{dT}{dt} = k(65 - T)</me>
      (because <m> k</m> is not specified as a positive or negative constant, either is fine.)
    </p>
  </answer>
</exercise>

  <exercise xml:id="ex-1-1-4">
    <statement>
      <p>
        Complete parts (a) and (b).
      </p>
    </statement>
    <task xml:id="ex-1-1-4a">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Verify that <m>y(x) = Ce^{-2x}</m> is a solution of <m>y' + 2y = 0</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <answer>
        <p>
          <me>y' + 2y = -2Ce^{-2x} + 2Ce^{-2x} = 0. \checkmark</me>
        </p>
      </answer>
    </task>
    <task xml:id="ex-1-1-4b">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Find the value of <m>C</m> satisfying the initial condition <m>y(0) = 4</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <answer>
        <p><m>C = 4</m>.</p>
      </answer>
    </task>
  </exercise>

  <exercise xml:id="ex-1-1-5">
    <statement>
      <p>
        Verify by substitution that <m>y_1 = \cos(5x)</m> and <m>y_2 = \sin(5x)</m> are both solutions of:
        <me>y'' + 25y = 0.</me>
      </p>
    </statement>
   
    <answer>
  <p>
    For <m>y_1 = \cos(5x)</m>: <m>y_1'' + 25y_1 = -25\cos(5x) + 25\cos(5x) = 0.</m> <m>\checkmark</m>
  </p>
  <p>
    For <m>y_2 = \sin(5x)</m>: <m>y_2'' + 25y_2 = -25\sin(5x) + 25\sin(5x) = 0.</m> <m>\checkmark</m>
  </p>
</answer>
  </exercise>

  <exercise xml:id="ex-1-1-6">
    <statement>
      <p>
        Verify by substitution that <m>y = 10e^x - 6e^{-x}</m> is a solution of:
        <me>y' = y + 12e^{-x}.</me>
      </p>
    </statement>
    
    <answer>
  <p>
    <m>y' = 10e^x + 6e^{-x}</m> and <m>y + 12e^{-x} = 10e^x + 6e^{-x}.</m> <m>\checkmark</m>
  </p>
</answer>
  </exercise>

  <exercise xml:id="ex-1-1-7">
    <statement>
      <p>
        Find all integer values of <m>n</m> for which <m>y(x) = x^n</m> is a solution to:
        <me>xy'' - y' - \frac{3y}{x} = 0.</me>
      </p>
    </statement>
    <answer>
      <p><m>n = 3</m> and <m>n = -1</m>.</p>
    </answer>
  </exercise>

  <exercise xml:id="ex-1-1-8">
    <statement>
      <p>
        Find all integer values of <m>n</m> for which <m>f(t) = t^n</m> is a solution to:
        <me>\frac{d^2f}{dt^2} + \frac{1}{t}\frac{df}{dt} = 0.</me>
      </p>
    </statement>
    <answer>
      <p><m>n = 0</m>.</p>
    </answer>
  </exercise>

  <exercise xml:id="ex-1-1-9">
    <statement>
      <p>
        Find all values of the constant <m>r</m> for which <m>y = e^{rx}</m> is a solution of:
        <me>y'' - y' - 6y = 0.</me>
      </p>
    </statement>
    <answer>
      <p><m>r = 3</m> and <m>r = -2</m>.</p>
    </answer>
  </exercise>

  <exercise xml:id="ex-1-1-10">
    <statement>
      <p>
        Find all equilibrium (constant) solutions to the equation below. That is, find all values of <m>C</m> for which <m>y(t) = C</m> is a solution.
        <me>y'' = e^{\cos t}\, y' - \sqrt{2t}\, y' + y^2 - t^2.</me>
      </p>
    </statement>
    <answer>
      <p>No equilibrium solutions.</p>
    </answer>
  </exercise>

  <exercise xml:id="ex-1-1-11">
    <statement>
      <p>
        Find all equilibrium (constant) solutions to the equation below. That is, find all values of <m>C</m> for which <m>\phi(q) = C</m> is a solution.
        <me>\frac{d\phi}{dq} + 9 = \phi^2 - q\frac{d\phi}{dq}.</me>
      </p>
    </statement>
    <answer>
      <p><m>\phi(q) = 3</m> and <m>\phi(q) = -3</m>.</p>
    </answer>
  </exercise>

  <p>
      The following calculus facts will be useful throughout these exercises. Feel free to use them as a quick reference!
    </p>
    <p>
      <alert>Calculus Prerequisites</alert>
    </p>
    <p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <p>
            <alert>Power Rule:</alert> <m>\dfrac{d}{dx}(x^n) = nx^{n-1}</m>
          </p>
          <solution>
            <title>Example</title>
            <p>
              <m>\dfrac{d}{dx}(x^3) = 3x^2</m>. We multiply by the exponent and reduce the power by 1.
            </p>
          </solution>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <alert>Exponential Rule:</alert> <m>\dfrac{d}{dx}(e^x) = e^x</m>, and more generally by the chain rule: <m>\dfrac{d}{dx}(e^{kx}) = ke^{kx}</m>
          </p>
          <solution>
            <title>Example</title>
            <p>
              <m>\dfrac{d}{dx}(e^{3x}) = 3e^{3x}</m>. The chain rule brings down the inner derivative <m>3</m> as a factor.
            </p>
          </solution>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <alert>Chain Rule:</alert> <m>\dfrac{d}{dx}(f(g(x))) = f'(g(x)) \cdot g'(x)</m>
          </p>
          <solution>
            <title>Example</title>
            <p>
              <m>\dfrac{d}{dx}(e^{x^2}) = e^{x^2} \cdot 2x = 2xe^{x^2}</m>. Here <m>f(u) = e^u</m> and <m>g(x) = x^2</m>, so <m>f'(g(x)) = e^{x^2}</m> and <m>g'(x) = 2x</m>.
            </p>
          </solution>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <alert>Product Rule:</alert> <m>\dfrac{d}{dx}(f(x)g(x)) = f'(x)g(x) + f(x)g'(x)</m>
          </p>
          <solution>
            <title>Example</title>
            <p>
              <m>\dfrac{d}{dx}(xe^x) = 1 \cdot e^x + x \cdot e^x = e^x(1+x)</m>.
            </p>
          </solution>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <alert>Trig Derivatives:</alert> <m>\dfrac{d}{dx}(\sin x) = \cos x</m> and <m>\dfrac{d}{dx}(\cos x) = -\sin x</m>
          </p>
        </li>
      </ul>
    </p>

<interactive xml:id="question-form-1-1-ex" iframe="question-form.html?section=1.1 exercises" width="100%" aspect="2:1"/>
</exercises>